	<text id="material" x="37" y="65" width="697" height="346" autosize="" style="WIZARD_TEXT" visible="true" fx="SHOW" hidefx="HIDE" scroll="AUTO">
		<content translate="true">&lt;P ALIGN="LEFT"&gt;&lt;B&gt;Discussion Topic&lt;/B&gt;&lt;/P&gt;&lt;P ALIGN="LEFT"&gt;One of your roles is to help caregivers understand how to best support children's healthy development.&lt;/P&gt;&lt;P ALIGN="LEFT"&gt;Let's look at a situation in which a caregiver has concerns about a childâ€™s development.&lt;/P&gt;&lt;P ALIGN="LEFT"&gt;&lt;/P&gt;&lt;P ALIGN="LEFT"&gt;&lt;B&gt;Scenario &lt;/B&gt;&lt;/P&gt;&lt;P ALIGN="LEFT"&gt;I'm excited for Henry to get a little older so that we can start interacting with each other. Right now, he doesn't do much except sleep and cry.&lt;/P&gt;&lt;P ALIGN="LEFT"&gt;&lt;B&gt;&lt;/B&gt;&lt;/P&gt;&lt;P ALIGN="LEFT"&gt;&lt;B&gt;Discussion Question&lt;/B&gt;&lt;/P&gt;&lt;P ALIGN="LEFT"&gt;Is this the correct attitude for a parent to have?&lt;/P&gt;&lt;P ALIGN="LEFT"&gt;&lt;/P&gt;&lt;P ALIGN="LEFT"&gt;&lt;B&gt;Sample Feedback &lt;/B&gt;&lt;/P&gt;&lt;P ALIGN="LEFT"&gt;Infants need to eat and sleep, but they also need to interact. Caregivers often think that newborns aren't doing anything so they shouldn't interact with a baby until the baby can respond verbally. This isn't true. In fact, interaction makes a big difference in a baby's development. &lt;/P&gt;&lt;P ALIGN="LEFT"&gt;&lt;/P&gt;&lt;P ALIGN="LEFT"&gt;Professionals should encourage caregivers to interact with babies from birth by singing, reading, and talking to them frequently.&lt;/P&gt;&lt;P ALIGN="LEFT"&gt;&lt;/P&gt;</content>
	</text>
